FogoMini is a pre-programmed RGB LED board designed and manufactured by Alternative Electronics. With FogoMini you can quickly implement your lamps and lithophanes. You can control it with the internal push button or an external touch sensor. And if you like programming, you can program its STM8 microcontroller.

The price of FogoMini is $ 85 MXN ($ 4.25 USD).

The FogoMini kit costs $ 120 MXN, ($ 6.00 USD).

item.title: Courier Singleship (small freighter spaceship)
item.description:
Here's a model of a spaceship for space-port scenarios in sci-fi skirmish games (or whatever other uses you can think of for it). I tried to make it of a realistic size, so it ends up quite a large model for 28mm - I used the size of modern single-seat military aircraft as a rough guide.

It will also make a decent toy spaceship for kids.

The uncut stl prints whole, positioned on my Ender 3 FDM printer if scaled down to 33% size (but will definitely need supports). The landing struts will be a little fragile if scaled down, so remove supports carefully

I included holes to accommodate bits of 1.7mm plastic filament in the mating faces of the cut up version parts to aid alignment during assembly, which I suggest you do with superglue or epoxy.

item.title: Yeti mug holder
item.description:
I remolded using original as template. I made it more rounded profile ,added an embossed Yeti and created a 10oz mug as well in same remix.

I took 1mm out of the bracket out so it is a tighter fit. I printed upright . did not modify connection point so you can still print original bracket

You need to lightly sand/file the bottom leading edges of the connection point (on mug holder) after print.
After light sand it fits perfectly into bracket. I tested this for both of my prints .

i used .6 nozzle on Flashforge CREATORPRO 2 PETG stock settings for temps

item.title: Railroad Boxcar for 32mm Gaming
item.description:
I needed a Railroad Boxcar as a scenario terrain piece for a horror game.
...but, I have been spoiled by a company that makes their buildings with removeable roofs, split layers, working doors, and accessible interiors.

So my goal is when remixing or creating designs, to make them more functional. and scaled for 32mm gaming.

I have rebuilt this boxcar, to have a removable roof, with slots to magnetize it. the side doors can slide open and closed. So the interior is accessible.

I have otherwise split and designed it to print the parts with minimal need for supports, so there is less clean up and support removal.

Prints fine on an Ender 3, when placed diagonally.

item.title: Made in USA stamp
item.description:
Use this stamp to show your pride in your products and where they're made!

The curved version can be used like a regular stamp, with either an inking pad or block printing ink rolled onto a glass palette. Heavily ink the printing surface of the stamp and roll onto your paper in a single side-to-side motion. If you need to rock the stamp side to side, you didn't use enough ink.

The flat version won't make a great stamp (since it isn't flexible) but is instead meant to be used like a block print. Ink the printing surface with an inking pad or apply block printing ink with a roller and place the stamp on a sturdy flat surface with the inked side facing up. Then, place your paper over the top and rub the back surface of the paper with a block printing baren or something similar (like a spoon), being careful not to shift the position of the paper on the stamp.

I printed this on an Anycubic Photon UVLED printer at a 0.05mm layer height without supports, and then sanded the ridges from the printing surface with #2000 sandpaper.

If you use this design on your products, please consider posting a picture in the makes section. I'd sure love to see it!

item.title: Compact pen holder clip
item.description:
A simple but satisfying clip to hold up to 6 standard hexagonal pens. With the right pens (~7.6mm inscribed circle diameter), they snap in securely making the full clip suitable to toss in your bag.

Click sound demo:
https://youtu.be/7spDEGcY_Mw

I printed in PETG because the clip deforms significantly as a pen is snapped in place. I presume PLA would get brittle very quickly and get damaged.
